This paper is likely to belong to the following arXiv CS sub-categories: 

1. cs.CL (Computation and Language): The paper introduces a new speech corpus designed for text-to-speech use, which falls under the domain of computational linguistics. 

2. cs.SD (Sound): The paper deals with speech data and its processing, which falls under the domain of sound. 

3. cs.SI (Speech Recognition and Synthesis): The paper discusses the use of the corpus for training and evaluating automatic speech recognition systems, which falls under the domain of speech recognition and synthesis. 

4. cs.LG (Machine Learning): The paper mentions the use of neural end-to-end TTS models, which falls under the domain of machine learning. 

5. cs.CC (Computational Complexity): Although less likely, this paper could also belong to the cs.CC sub-category as it deals with the complexity of processing speech data for text-to-speech use.
